exit 0” denotes that the command is successfully executed
exit 1” (non-zero status) identifies an error in the shell script. It usually occurs when an incorrect argument
 is passed to the command.
exit 2”  is another non-zero value that also specifies the error occurrence in the shell script. 
It generally occurs when the script cannot find the targeted file.

$*" special parameter takes the entire list as one argument with spaces between and the 
"$@" special parameter takes the entire list and separates it into separate arguments.

-------------------------------------------------
$@ = stores all the arguments in a list of string
$* = stores all the arguments as a single string
$# = stores the number of arguments
